SIMPLE: insulated
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insulated
<hw>In"su*la`ted</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"s⟦usl⟧*l⟦amac⟧"t⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>p.
a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Standing by itself; not being contiguous to
other bodies; separated; unconnected; isolated; <as>as, an
<ex>insulated</ex> house or column</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The special and <qex>insulated</qex> situation of the Jews.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Elect. & Thermotics)</fld> <def>Separated from
other bodies by means of nonconductors of heat or electricity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Situated at so great a distance
as to be beyond the effect of gravitation; -- said of stars supposed to
be so far apart that the affect of their mutual attraction is
insensible.</def> <rj><au>C. A. Young.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Insulated wire</b></col>, <cd>wire covered with some
nonconducting material, such as plastic or silk, for use in conducting
electricity.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insulation</ent>⟦br⟧
